roblem and the social unease out of which it emerged provided a rationale for reimagining governance in education, liberalizing the job market, and a new role for psychology in the overturning of national-cultural ideologies. The Strange Child uncovers the state of nationalism in contemporary Japan, the politics of distraction around the child, and the altered life conditions of-and alternatives created by-the recessionary generation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEducationxPsychological aspectsxJapan. 0aEducationxSocial aspectsxJapan. 0aEducationxSocial aspectszJapan. 0aEducationzJapanxPsychological aspects. 0aNational characteristics, Japanese. 0aPatriotismxJapan. 0aPatriotismzJapan. 0aRecessionsxSocial aspectsxJapan. 0aRecessionsxSocial aspectszJapan. 4aalternatives. 4aeducation. 4ajob hunting. 4along-term ethnography. 4aneoliberal patriotism. 4apsychology. 4arecession. 4arecessionary generation. 4atemporality. 4athe child. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479856340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804798563423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804798563.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles